# 📅 Day 9 – C++ Fundamentals

# 1️⃣ Constructor & Destructor

Before learning definitions, first understand the PROBLEM.

---

# Problem Without Constructor

Imagine creating a student object:

```cpp id="mw5fmb"
class Student
{
public:
    string name;
    int age;
};
```

Now:

```cpp id="1owpru"
Student s1;
```

Problem:

```text id="pjlwm9"
name → garbage/empty
age → garbage value
```

We want automatic initialization.

---

# Solution → Constructor

---

# What is a Constructor?

👉 Special function that runs automatically when object is created.

---

# Real-World Example

Think of buying a phone.

The moment phone starts:

* memory initialized
* system loaded
* apps prepared

Automatic setup.

That’s constructor behavior.

---

# Example

```cpp id="jlwmg6"
class Student
{
public:

    string name;

    Student()
    {
        name = "Akshay";
    }
};
```

---

# What Happens?

When:

```cpp id="i0j33l"
Student s1;
```

is created:

Constructor runs automatically.

---

# Output

```cpp id="u4llf5"
cout << s1.name;
```

👉

```text id="jlwm4l"
Akshay
```

---

# Why Constructor Exists

To:

* initialize objects
* avoid garbage values
* automate setup

---

# Mental Model (Never Forget)

```text id="jlwm34"
Constructor = automatic setup function
```

---

# Important Properties

| Property           | Meaning                |
| ------------------ | ---------------------- |
| same name as class | mandatory              |
| no return type     | not even void          |
| runs automatically | during object creation |

---

# Parameterized Constructor

---

## Example

```cpp id="yjlwmn"
class Student
{
public:

    string name;

    Student(string n)
    {
        name = n;
    }
};
```

Usage:

```cpp id="jlwmq3"
Student s1("Akshay");
```

---

# Why Useful?

Different objects can have different values.

---

# Real-World Analogy

```text id="jlwmf2"
Car(color)
Phone(model)
Student(name)
```

---

# Destructor

Now opposite concept.

---

# What is Destructor?

👉 Special function that runs automatically when object is destroyed.

---

# Real-World Example

When leaving hotel room:

* lights off
* resources cleaned
* room freed

Cleanup process.

---

# Example

```cpp id="jlwmu8"
class Test
{
public:

    ~Test()
    {
        cout << "Object Destroyed";
    }
};
```

---

# Symbol Meaning

```cpp id="jlwm1s"
~
```

called:

```text id="jlwmcx"
tilde
```

---

# Why Destructor Exists

To:

* release memory
* close files
* clean resources

Very important in large systems.

---

# Mental Model

```text id="jlwm0v"
Constructor → setup
Destructor → cleanup
```

---

# Constructor vs Destructor

| Constructor         | Destructor       |
| ------------------- | ---------------- |
| creates/setup       | destroys/cleanup |
| automatic           | automatic        |
| same name           | ~className       |
| can have parameters | no parameters    |

